Given that the file to be generated is package.json, there's no need to worry about TypeScript typings or HTML5 Canvas utilization in this case. Here's a basic package.json setup for a Next.js project:

json
{
  "name": "your-nextjs-project",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "Description of your Next.js project",
  "main": "index.js",
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "next dev",
    "build": "next build",
    "start": "next start",
    "lint": "next lint"
  },
  "keywords": [
    "nextjs",
    "react",
    "typescript"
  ],
  "author": "",
  "license": "ISC",
  "dependencies": {
    "next": "latest",
    "react": "^17.0.2",
    "react-dom": "^17.0.2"
  },
  "devDependencies": {
    "@types/react": "^17.0.11",
    "@typescript-eslint/eslint-plugin": "^4.28.0",
    "@typescript-eslint/parser": "^4.28.0",
    "eslint": "^7.30.0",
    "eslint-config-next": "^11.0.1",
    "typescript": "^4.3.5"
  }
}


Modify the "name", "description", "author", and "license" fields as necessary for your project. The scripts listed allow you to start your development server, build your project for production, start your production server, and run linting checks with Next.js's built-in ESLint configuration.

The "dependencies" section includes the necessary packages for a Next.js project: Next.js itself, React, and ReactDOM. In the "devDependencies" section, we have TypeScript and packages related to ESLint for linting TypeScript and React code.

Remember to run `npm install` or `yarn install` to install these dependencies after setting up your package.json file.